eriods, from the early 1960s to the present. Among the subjects he highlights are travel and colonialism in fieldwork and filmmaking, orientalism in the representation of the Other, and the film's ambiguous handling of masculinity and homosexuality. Caton looks at his own reactions to the film at various stages in his life and offers a thought-provoking account of the film's reception by today's high school and college students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArabs in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aaqaba.  aarab national council.  abritish film.  aclass.  aclassic film.  acolonialism.  acultural differences.  adamascus.  adesert tribes.  adiscourse of power.  aemotional struggles.  aepic historical drama.  aethnography.  afilm and television.  afilm criticism.  afilm studies.  afilm.  afilmmaking.  afirst world war.  agender studies.  agender.  agreater syria.  ahejaz.  ahomosexuality.  aidentity.  alawrence of arabia.  amasculinity.  amiddle east.  amovie studies.  amovies.  aottoman empire.  arepresentation of the other.  ate lawrence.  aviolence.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021083740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919891?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919891/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY